    {
      "text": "A 35-year-old male presented with a history of a femur fracture from a road traffic accident 8 months ago. He was treated with a cast, but now has a deformity with leg shortening and limping. An X-ray shows abnormal alignment of the fractured bone. Which of the following is the most appropriate management for this patient?",
      "options": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "Continue conservative treatment",
          "correct": false
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "Open reduction and internal fixation (ORIF) with bone grafting",
          "correct": true
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "Physical therapy to correct the deformity",
          "correct": false
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "External fixation for deformity correction",
          "correct": false
        }
      ],
      "correct_answer": "B. Open reduction and internal fixation (ORIF) with bone grafting",
